rComments: Megan is a great instructor who is genuinely invested in your success. The beginning of the rotation I found her intimidating, but once I adjusted I realized how fortunate I was to be learning from her. She encourages self-direction and critical thinking, both essential skills in nursing. Be prepared and open to feedback and you'll succeed!

Megan is one of the best instructors Ive ever had. She makes you work hard and wont put up with you being you being unprepared but if youre willing to put in the effort she will teach you how to bring your knowledge and practice to the next professional level.

This is an easy A course but Manning spends most of her time dehumanizing and humiliating students rather than teaching. The lectures are poorly organized, fragmented and verbose. She blatantly ignores emails and is very difficult to approach. Avoid!
The level of bullying directed at other students was not okay. Nurses eat their young is her slogan. Avoid for clinical placements.

I have post traumatic stress from having Megan. She bullies students like I have never experienced and other clinical instructors are aware. When asked about my regimented way of giving meds and why my hands shake like no other, clinical instructors understood when I said I had this instructor prior. Avoid!
Horrible clinical instructor. I still have PTSD level flashbacks from having her for clinical in third year. She bullies students.
Lectures are dull and all over the place, difficult to reach and bullies students. Avoid!

She is a very caring prof and want to help her students . She is a big supporter of self-directed learning so if you ask her a question she will help you find resources that will give you an answer. YOU NEED TO READ THE TEXTBOOK . If you do this it will definitely help you understand the course content . Overall she was a good prof.
teacherRatingTags: ['Get ready to read', 'Caring', 'Graded by few things']

rComments: Megan is an amazing clinical instructor. I have never had a clinical instructor care so much about her students and get so invested in their learning. She really helps to guide and grow your critical thinking skills & she sets you up with a great foundation that continue throughout your nsg career. I wish I could have her for all my placements:)

Megan is an amazing clinical instructor! I had her for my surgical rotation and would consider her to be my favourite instructor. She has clear expectations & tries to get everyone the opportunity to practice NSG skills. She also does a great job of applying course content & making you critically think about pt. values and NSG interventions. 10/10!

Megan was a phenomenal professor. She had clear high expectations for the group, but was always available for clarification and direction. You will learn so much from this teacher, and learn how to be more self-directed in learning yourself! Def would want her again!

Megan was my clinical instructor and she's been by far my favorite. She was awesome !! Her expectations were always super clear, she asks you questions to try and get you to think more about your patient's status. She was very encouraging and supportive whenever I had questions and I learned so much from her , I wish the rotation was longer!

Intimidating. We had to write a paper on health promotion and she didn't give anyone a straight answer as to what she was expecting of us. Exam was mediocre, fairly straightforward. Frustrating to get information from her and relevant feedback.

rComments: Would do anything not to have her again. Little feedback, unclear expectations, and my group was constantly criticized. If you cry, make sure you do it in the supply room or you will get torn apart publicly.
